The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would force the classics to discount.
Maybe he won't be missing for a long time.
About the fact that Czech operators are one of the most expensive in Europe, we have written on Mobil.cz many times.
This was also confirmed by the CTU, who warned that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to get into the fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and penetration is over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to argue that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
They are often quoted by the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (CTE), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, who in the past said several times that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It’s probably true that a classic operator with his own network probably doesn’t have too many chances anymore (by the way, it’s probably just hard to look for frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought significant price cuts, to which also the classic operators had to react.
In the UK, before the entry of plugs like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, voices like ours were heard.
However, it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to operate effectively, they have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good draw and betting on an unfired target group.
This operator is specifically aimed at men.
“Administrative guys choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept could be caught in Poland as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic without a chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look too hopeful.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a press spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
She indirectly confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they are trying to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has long been uncovered by the GTS Novar Group, which would like to take the next step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only solid, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
This option has been discussed with all Czech mobile operators over and over again.
With some of them, we have already managed to make progress in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
So maybe he's flipping for better times.
It appears from informal information that we should expect the first virtual operator perhaps by the end of the year.
But for now, its formation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"We do not think that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been contacted by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>en<0xC4><0x9B> from the Telefónica O2 press department said in a statement for Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also appealed to by other operators.
Press spokeswoman for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rarely compliant with the statement of O2: "In the meantime, we have not recorded any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further."
He added: “In the T-Mobile network, by the end of the year, virtual operators will hardly appear.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table so that it would be possible to consider this short horizon."
Vodafone refuses to pay attention to the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: “We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The procedure of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to a drop in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when it comes to something, the operators are able to pull a rope, they are also witnesses to the formation of the U:fon.
Probably the biggest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>TU was at the time of the creation of U:fona by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>TU website.
Now, however, U:fon fits as an argument for why a virtual operator is not allowed.
Martina Kemrová added: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been reinforced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and above all on his services."
However, due to this approach of mobile operators, there is a total disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
It is not just about the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere in economic competition.
They belong exclusively to the Competition Protection Office (ECSC).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between a mobile operator and a virtual operator to lease the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has yet been concluded, as the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for classic operators," said Kristian Chalupa of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS External Relations Department in response to our question.
It is not surprising to the representatives of the operators.
From an authority to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market, it is more than a matter of consideration.
Particularly when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In the overseas, where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lowering prices for mobile phone services."
However, it seems that the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the price decline are not in the interest of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
In fact, shockingly over the whole case is the imposing conviction of three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is offered entirely on its own.
As well as the exact same price of gasoline at gas stations is certainly just part of a coincidence and a tough competition fight.
"The Authority has not sought evidence of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore has no correspondingly increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile market for virtual operators are also likely to meet the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the CTU, according to which telecommunications are, from the point of view of competition, the single market.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - for the creation of a virtual operator, the consent of the network operator is always required.
And the mobile operator - it has quite a logic - on its network monopoly.
So in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
However, even if we do not accept this argument, it should be a minimum warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are acting noticeably similarly.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Nowera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in dealing with all operators.
In telecommunications, <0xC3><0x9A>OHS is a fairly common trick, which takes away from the whole issue.
We’ve met him on a number of similar occasions.
Unfortunately, until the recent adoption of the Telecommunications Act, the extension of <0xC4><0x8C>TU’s powers to the field of competition in telecommunications did not succeed, although a number of experts have promised an improvement in the situation.
<0xC3><0x9A>OHS representatives must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
That's what happens when no one's looking
At the same time, the operation of some pseudovirtual operators remains unnoticed, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that issue their own pricelists for mobile phone services, but are only partially public.
This is usually a multi-level marketing business.
Its own mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The prices of these companies will usually only reach the selected ones.
The charm lies in the fact that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders large amounts of SIM cards.
As an important customer, you will then receive special price (and additional) offers.
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there were cases you're talking about, it could be a violation of the terms of the contract that we would deal with and could result in termination of cooperation with the company," said Martina Kamrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that such activity would not affect the responsible people from mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators will prevent such a move.
In fact, these companies have unnoticed profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not in any way endanger their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, however, the services of these companies use only a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not held in their name, so they cannot be fully available to them as regular customers of mobile operators."
But that should be at least strange to read.
In addition, another question opens up for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to a similar process, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has a relatively strong authority to disclose similar activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the operators’ explanation that they have no idea of such a thing and their trading conditions prohibit it.
When We Will Not Be the Most Expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a marked decline in service prices.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, the classic operators were more or less trying to defend their creation.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small, perhaps too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, regulatory authorities have intervened in these moments, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether it was formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator was created, and more were added to it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities overheat the whole case like hot potatoes.
From our experience we cannot get rid of the impression that the uncertainty in their competences is more than suitable for them in these cases.
But let's not put the flour in the grain.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator appears with us very soon, the Czech mobile market may be shifting again.
If one of the operators has admitted the emergence of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain ineffective in refusing (discrimination) other stakeholders.
Perhaps we will stop calling the ride than in the rest of Europe.
