But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we begin to devote ourselves to a different kind and open up questions of perception or general awareness, we enter into the indifferent terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets in danger, he will do the same as many other animals: he will pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists suggest a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it easier to transfer our subjective experience to the experience of animals.
It is also because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its share of short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This vast area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and seems to be completely missing in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to assume that man is different even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be hidden by the linguistic nature of man: because so much of his perception is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on him.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness did not matter to language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, no matter how constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness might look like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it is not possible to measure or, because of special hardware, to be analyzed on the basis of our own experience, its exploration puts us in great trouble.
Most of my findings relate to the content of the conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to examine processes in the animal consciousness regardless of their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially for example visualization.
But this approach, devoted to Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses more on neural correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but perhaps they are not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of nonfrontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
