Conversation - Blood that is sure again
Hema-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly pleased because Hema-Québec has become one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
In particular, he regained public trust, which was severely shaken after the blood-contaminated scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is commonly known, the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Board’s state-owned blood reserve was contaminated by the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and public discontent, in February 1994, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and to formulate a recommendation to prevent such a tragedy from happening.
While Judge Krever hesitated to deliver the report, some provinces put in place a committee aimed at scheduling a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec this role was assumed by the Gélinea Committee.
Following Gélineau and Krever's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to be managed by Québec, and the Canadian Blood Company for the supply of all provinces and both territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
“The situation was awkward.
By consistent efforts to increase the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area, we have regained public trust over the next few years," he says, adding proudly that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Québec population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that “trust is something very fragile.”
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
“At that time, we were witnessing in Europe many human-like cases of mad cow disease, new variants of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,” says a woman who has been leading the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread with blood.
We have therefore fought for one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau report, according to which, in the event that we do not know this and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain, must be prevented by death.
In April 1999, therefore, we rejected blood from people who had been detained in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that the disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to stick to the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow to detect in the donor blood the presence of the virus itself, rather than the presence of antibodies on which the tests were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of the patient’s infection and the moment when our technicians can detect the first virus in the blood, the specialist explains.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We have substantially reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing it and without we being able to lose sight of it.
This improvement has significantly reduced the risk of acquiring AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
In other words, it means that before someone becomes infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will need to be distributed.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe blood transfusions necessary for healing,” said Héma-Québec chief executive.
“The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogenic element can appear in the system.
Just last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, similar to the West Nile virus, which is transmitted to the blood by puncturing insects.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," continues Dr. Décary and stresses that in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also count on sufficient supply.
“Needs are growing as the population grows older.
As a result of more aggressive treatment of cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for donation."
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, which meets the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people offering blood are not accepted because, for example, they have AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited the country where they have had a cold, they are excluded for one year.
“With these 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
Members of the donor network, however, need to be supplemented in proportion to how old they are and can no longer donate blood.
However, persuading people to donate blood is difficult, especially then keeping them and encouraging them to become regular donors.
“Life is so unpredictable today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of <0x24>297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues such as bone transplants, heart palates, eye potatoes and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public bank of blood from the pup cord in Quebec.
Puppy cord, which was previously considered a biomedical waste, flows with blood rich on stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand samples of blood from the pup cord into the bank and we assume we will take them out over a thousand a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants,” says Dr. Décary, who describes the blood sample program as very popular.
"Some moms are disappointed that they don't have access to it," because Héma-Québec doesn't have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
