Psychology of Trumpfing: Why We Spend More Money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known – and seemingly irrational – behavior were revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics at the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people in the eBay auction type competition do not want to delay, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
The research, using an experimental auction, attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers wagered, the other group participated in the auctions, using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method to examine the active areas of the brain of the subjects.
In both games, the participants were able to win money, however, during the auction game, an important element of which is to overlap the other side, the whole under the brain cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively while losing.
This area of the brain plays, among many other functions, a role in the “self-rewarding” mechanism of the nervous system.
Screwing the price, therefore, according to the researchers, can be explained by trying to avoid a sharp striate reaction.
To support their theory, members of the research team from a number of economists conducted financial cross-sectional research.
At the same time, three groups have auctioned against one partner on different terms.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product, and they made the bets.
In addition, members of the other group were promised that if they left the game winners, they would receive another <0x24>15 for reward.
The third group received <0x24>15, on the other hand, before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost that money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, that one was highlighted by winning and the other by losing.
However, the members of the group playing "against loss" were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the neurologists' hypothesis.
“These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
They have so far explained the phenomena observed in the auctions of joy of victory and avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped us solve the conflict between these two theories, so we have now reached the third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to See a Doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, however, only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is an aggregate name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, symptom is hepatitis and jaundice, however the origins of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways depending on the origin of the disease: hepatitis type A and E by digestive means (e.g. by infected food, water), hepatitis type B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body fluids (sperm, mucous membranes).
In any case, travelers should be protected by vaccination against viruses A and B, the type C vaccine does not exist.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the ingestion of the infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, the urge to vomit.
Then, yellowing, lightening stools and darkening urine are formed on the skin and whitening of the eyes. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in 10 infected is medicated.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease, the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells contagiously, and thus the first symptoms will appear in many cases up to 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, the implementation of regular screening.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more often than the average: among people who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can already prove a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his/her doctor if he/she notices any signs of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infection and preventing the onset of cancer.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized worldwide in 2004 by organisations representing the sick.
Its aim is to highlight the chronic liver inflammation caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Who believes in God doesn’t hurt that much?
According to recent research, faith in God acts as a certain analgesic that could ease the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how a person’s belief in the God of pain perception affects, the British daily Telegraph reported.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while all of them watched a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholics were able to exclude much of the pain.
Thanks to the technique that investigates the human brain in detail, it has also been shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first of a series of research, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university participate.
The exact test was carried out by attaching a sparkling instrument to the left hand of the experimental subject, which emitted electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to carefully observe two paintings: the 17th-century Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's painting, painted in the 15th-century.
The authors of the study hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would cause a certain state of piety among the believers, while the da Vinci painting was chosen because it was not too different from the first and seems to them to be a soothing impression.
The subjects spent half an hour in the MRI scanner and during this time received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive parts, while separately watching an image with a religious or general theme.
The Catholics said they felt "safe" when looking at the Virgin Mary, as if they were "settled" and "relaxed, they were filled with peace."
When watching a picture with a religious theme, they said they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonard’s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with the help of any highly influential image even in atheists, it is only necessary to find the right photograph.
“We should find a picture that will be very positive from the position of a mother or father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it will also change our personality,” Wright added.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on the pain management of believers if they were shown a madonna by Leonardo or a painter of a similar caliber.
Would a look at the quality of the Virgin Mary mean even better results?
