The original strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the CEATEC in Japan, injected boots to engineers from Nissan. It was about how to build a new generation of collision-preventing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetric robotic steering system, a robotic mini car equipped with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
“Throughout the summer, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging,” explained Kazuhiro Doi, Brand Director for Technology PR and Research and Development at the exhibition.
Composite eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eye, engineers came up with the idea of a laser telescope.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters away from BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into a collision prevention operation.
The obstacle is captured during a fraction of a second, then the robotized car begins to mimic the movements of the bees and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent collision immediately changes the direction.
Unlike any existing system, this destructive maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
“If it weren’t, the robotic car wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Robotic Car Mobility Laboratory and Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety protective packaging, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what bees do to avoid further bees.
This process should not take longer than the eye blinking.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or perpendicularly, it can be only two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotational movement, acceleration and slowdown was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer accumulators that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Andoa, instinctive, intelligent responses are important, not the ability to process, but less data storage.
This mechanism must process and respond only to a few incoming signals in a second.
It is not necessary to store and react using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so only memory of a few kilobytes is constantly used.
It does not require memory with giga or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing technology for immediate avoidance, which Nissan estimates is likely to get into serial-produced cars within a decade.
Another option may be to connect the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles in the road, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
